# natural_language_idea: How many different linear arrangements are there of the letters A,
#                        B, C, D, E, F for which (a) A and B are next to each other? (b) Ai
#                        sb e f o r eB? (c) A is before B and B is before C? (d) A is before
#                        B and C is before D? (e) A and B are next to each other and C and D
#                        are also next to each other? (f) E is not last in line?
# litex_code: this file
# proof_attempt: Start from labeled permutations. Identify the internal swaps that do not
#                change the visible outcome. Use quotient counting by repeated classes.
#                Evaluate n! divided by the product of repeated-class factorials.
